":[{"number":1,"category":"marriage","header":"She and her sisters all married Hart brothers","body":"She was one of three daughters of John Hooker Esq. of Farmington who each married a son of Capt. John Hart — Abigail to Nathaniel, Mary to Samuel, and Sarah to Matthew — between 1719 and 1725, uniting the two most prominent families of Farmington's founding generation."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Three sons served the Revolution differently","body":"Her eldest son Selah rose to General and was captured by the British in 1776; Noadiah served as Lieutenant; and Asahel, Yale-educated and ordained as a minister, died in 1775 at age 33 before the war's outcome was known. Three brothers from one Hooker-Hart household, three paths through the Revolution."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I00029","display_label":"Brother-in-law via Hart-Hooker triple marriage, 1719-1726","link_text":"Lieut. Samuel Hart","notes":"One of the three Hart-Hooker marriages between 1719 and 1726: three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030) married three sons of Capt. John Hart (X00033). Lieut. Samuel Hart married Abigail Hooker's sister Mary Hooker (H00100) in 1723; Abigail Hooker married I00028 in 1719."},{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"I00030","display_label":"Brother-in-law via Hart-Hooker triple marriage, 1719-1726","link_text":"Matthew Hart","notes":"One of the three Hart-Hooker marriages between 1719 and 1726: three daughters of Hon. John Hooker (H00030) married three sons of Capt. John Hart (X00033). Matthew Hart married Abigail Hooker's sister Sarah Hooker (H00101) in 1726; Abigail Hooker married I00028 in 1719."},{"type":"in_law","related_id":"X00033","display_label":"was her father-in-law; Hartford founding Hart family"}],"bio":{"display_name":"Abigail Hooker Hart","first_name":"Abigail","last_name":"Hart","married_names":["Hart"],"maiden_name":"Hooker"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"docume